Static Nested Class in Java

A static nested class is a class defined inside another class using the static keyword.

👉 It belongs to the outer class, but does not need an instance of it.

Basic Example
class Outer {
    static class Nested {
        void print() {
            System.out.println("Hello from static nested class");
        }
    }
}
Creating an Object
Outer.Nested obj = new Outer.Nested();
obj.print();

👉 No need to create Outer object

Key Features
declared with static
does NOT depend on outer class instance
can access only static members of outer class
behaves like a normal class, but scoped inside another
Accessing Outer Class Members
class Outer {
    static int x = 10;
    int y = 20;

    static class Nested {
        void print() {
            System.out.println(x); // ✅ allowed
            // System.out.println(y); ❌ not allowed
        }
    }
}
Why use Static Nested Class?

Use it when:

class is logically related to outer class
but does NOT need access to instance data
want better code organization
Real-Life Use

Often used for:

helper classes
builder patterns
grouping related logic
Static Nested vs Inner Class
Feature	Static Nested	Inner Class
Needs outer object	❌	✅
Access to instance fields	❌	✅
Access to static fields	✅	✅
Summary
static nested class = class inside class with static
no outer instance needed
can access only static members of outer class
used for better structure and organization
